Steven Taschuk wrote:

&gt; Quoth Berin Loritsch:
&gt;   [...]
&gt; &gt; The whole Name thing is irrelevant at this point.  If a Test
&gt; &gt; implements the TestFixture interface, then it will use reflection
&gt; &gt; to pull all the interfaces.  So the interface should be something
&gt; &gt; like this:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; interface TestFixture
&gt; &gt; {}
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; When the Test Collector/Test Runner runs across any Class
&gt; &gt; implementing TestFixture, it is converted into a group of
&gt; &gt; Test objects.  [...]
&gt;
&gt; Um.  Perhaps I&#39;m missing the point, but I&#39;d prefer to have the
&gt; Test-creation logic outside of the TestRunner.  For example:
&gt;
&gt;         interface TestFactory {
&gt;                 Test makeTest();
&gt;         }
&gt;
&gt;         class OneMethodTest implements Test {
&gt;                 OneMethodTest( Class c, Method m ) {
&gt;                         // ...
&gt;                 }
&gt;                 void run( TestResult result ) {
&gt;                         // instantiate c
&gt;                         // execute instance.setUp()
&gt;                         // execute instance.m
&gt;                         // execute instance.tearDown()
&gt;                 }
&gt;                 // ...
&gt;         }
&gt;
&gt;         class ReflectiveTestFactory implements TestFactory {
&gt;                 ReflectiveTestFactory() {
&gt;                         // factory based on self
&gt;                 }
&gt;                 ReflectiveTestFactory( Class c ) {
&gt;                         // factory based on class c
&gt;                 }
&gt;                 Test makeTest() {
&gt;                         // scan c (or self) for test* methods
&gt;                         // make a OneMethodTest for each
&gt;                         // return a TestSuite containing those
&gt;                 }
&gt;         }
&gt;
&gt; For backwards compatibility, a TestRunner encountering a TestCase
&gt; can make a ReflectiveFactory for it.  In general it expects to
&gt; encounter TestFactory implementations and let them make the Tests.
&gt;
&gt; For new test implementations, it is sufficient to put test*
&gt; methods in a subclass of ReflectiveFactory.  This is just like
&gt; subclassing TestCase now, but there&#39;s no need for the String
&gt; constructor (which might, as Meyers implied elsewhere in the
&gt; thread, encourage novice users to put setup in setUp() instead of
&gt; in the constructor).
&gt;
&gt; If it is inconvenient to subclass ReflectiveFactory (as when the
&gt; tests rely on partaking of some other inheritance hierarchy), it
&gt; is convenient enough to write
&gt;
&gt;         class MyTests implements TestFactory {
&gt;                 Test makeTest() {
&gt;                         return new ReflectiveTestFactory(
&gt;                                 this.getClass() ).makeTest();
&gt;                 }
&gt;                 // ...
&gt;         }
&gt;
&gt; As with the static suite() method, the advantage of this approach
&gt; is that tests can be generated however is desired.  Unlike
&gt; suite(), makeTest() above is an instance method, which as
&gt; Silverstein points out elsewhere in the thread makes it easier to
&gt; make tests from other frameworks work as JUnit tests.
